  title = {Redistributing {{Income}} to the {{Poor}} and the {{Rich}} : {{Public Transfers}} in {{Latin America}} and the {{Caribbean}}},
  abstract = {This study measures the extent to which publicly-subsidized transfers in Latin America and the\$$\backslash$backslash\$nCaribbean (LAC) redistribute income. The redistributive power of 56 transfers in eight countries is\$$\backslash$backslash\$nmeasured by their coverage, size, absolute incidence, simulated impacts on poverty and inequality, and\$$\backslash$backslash\$nby their distributional characteristic, a statistic derived from taxation literature.\$$\backslash$backslash\$nOur findings suggest that public transfers can be effective instruments to redistribute income to the\$$\backslash$backslash\$npoor. Yet frequently they have not managed to do so. Indeed, Robin Hood works in both directions\$$\backslash$backslash\$nin LAC, with public transfers redistributing income to both the rich and the poor. The redistributive\$$\backslash$backslash\$nimpacts from social insurance are limited \textendash{} and even regressive in some countries. This regressivity\$$\backslash$backslash\$nderives from two main design factors: a truncation in coverage due to requirements of membership in\$$\backslash$backslash\$nformal labor markets which exclude the majority of the poor, and highly generous unit benefits for\$$\backslash$backslash\$nthose in the upper quintiles. Moreover, this regressivity applies to net social insurance transfers, which\$$\backslash$backslash\$nare subsidized by government budgets at the expense of all taxpayers. The more recent emergence of\$$\backslash$backslash\$nsocial assistance only partially offsets this historical ``truncation'' of public transfers in LAC. Despite\$$\backslash$backslash\$ncoverage and distributional patterns that favor the poor, small unit subsidies limit the redistributive,\$$\backslash$backslash\$npoverty and inequality impacts of even the most targeted social assistance programs. We also find\$$\backslash$backslash\$nconsiderable variation among social assistance programs, with many food-based programs and\$$\backslash$backslash\$nscholarships being regressive. Governments should reconsider these programs \textendash{} or at least strengthen\$$\backslash$backslash\$ntheir design. They could look to the targeting mechanisms used by conditional cash transfers \textendash{} with\$$\backslash$backslash\$nimpressive rewards for progressivity},
